"n\">norm_num</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"bp\">|</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">succ</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">n</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">ih</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">=&gt;</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"k\">calc</span>\n<span class=\"w\">      </span><span class=\"n\">T</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">n</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">+</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">1</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">n</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">+</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">1</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">+</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">T</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">n</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">by</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">rw</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"n\">T</span><span class=\"o\">]</span>\n<span class=\"w\">      </span><span class=\"bp\">_</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">n</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">+</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">1</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">+</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">n</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">*</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">n</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">+</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">1</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">/</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">2</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">by</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">rw</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"n\">ih</span><span class=\"o\">]</span>\n<span class=\"w\">      </span><span class=\"bp\">_</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">n</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">+</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">1</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">*</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">n</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">+</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">1</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">+</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">1</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">/</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">2</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">by</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">ring</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"n\">norm_cast</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>I will have to look up what exactly <code>norm_cast</code> does, but my primitive current understanding is that it \"normalizes\" coercions or smth like that.</p>",
        "id": 491210156,
        "sender_full_name": "Ilmārs Cīrulis",
        "timestamp": 1735509077
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><code>⊢ (↑n + 1) * (↑n + 1 + 1) / 2 = ↑(n + 1) * (↑(n + 1) + 1) / 2</code> - this means that you still have goal to prove. As one can see, left side isn't equal to right side.</p>",
        "id": 491210278,
        "sender_full_name": "Ilmārs Cīrulis",
        "timestamp": 1735509199
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I don't understand why Lean thinks the LHS and RHS are different.</p>",
        "id": 491210421,
        "sender_full_name": "rzeta0",
        "timestamp": 1735509332
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>For example, <code>(↑n + 1)</code> and <code>↑(n + 1)</code> are different.<br>\nThe first is <code>n</code> converted to Q and then with rational number 1 added.<br>\nThe second is <code>n</code> as natural number with natural number 1 added and then the sum converted to Q.</p>",
        "id": 491210762,
        "sender_full_name": "Ilmārs Cīrulis",
        "timestamp": 1735509643
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The only thing that comes to mind is to use brackets to get Lean to think of <code>(n+1)</code> as a unit. I tried that and it didn't work.</p>\n<p>I also tried things like <code>((n + 1):ℚ)</code> which also didn't work.</p>",
        "id": 491211145,
        "sender_full_name": "rzeta0",
        "timestamp": 1735510033
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>But in any case, I feel doing coercions is probably the wrong approach.</p>",
        "id": 491211224,
        "sender_full_name": "rzeta0",
        "timestamp": 1735510089
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><code>(↑(n + 1) : ℚ)</code> will do what you expect</p>",
        "id": 491211271,
        "sender_full_name": "Yaël Dillies",
        "timestamp": 1735510155
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The theorem <code>Nat.cast_succ</code> proves that <code>↑(n + 1) = (↑n + 1)</code>.</p>",
        "id": 491211348,
        "sender_full_name": "Dan Velleman",
        "timestamp": 1735510204
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I suspect that you defined <code>T n</code> to be a rational number because your theorem was going to involve division by 2, and division is easier in Q than in N.  But by using Q, you were forced to deal with coercions.  An alternative would be to state your theorem as <code>2 * (T n) = n * (n + 1)</code>.  Now there's no division, so no reason to use Q rather than N.</p>",
        "id": 491211543,
        "sender_full_name": "Dan Velleman",
        "timestamp": 1735510426
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Thanks Ilmārs, Yaël and Dan.</p>\n<p>Overall I feel that casting is an ugly \"hack\" - I will go away and think if there is a better way for what I had hoped would be a nice simple educational example. </p>\n<p>If I can get the definition to be <code>ℕ→ℕ</code> that would avoid the casting, but then I need to solve <code>ring</code> failing.</p>",
        "id": 491211592,
        "sender_full_name": "rzeta0",
        "timestamp": 1735510444
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>And once you've proven the theorem in this new form, you could divide both sides by 2 to get the theorem you really wanted.</p>",
        "id": 491211613,
        "sender_full_name": "Dan Velleman",
        "timestamp": 1735510477
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Hi <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"453098\">@Dan Velleman</span>  - yes, <code>2*T</code> is the approach I used when I previously defined <code>Triangle</code> as a proposition and that was ok - but I was hoping to avoid it at this later stage of the learning journey.</p>\n<p><a href=\"https://leanfirststeps.blogspot.com/2024/11/19-our-own-definition.html\">https://leanfirststeps.blogspot.com/2024/11/19-our-own-definition.html</a></p>",
        "id": 491211727,
        "sender_full_name": "rzeta0",
        "timestamp": 1735510572
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"453098\">Dan Velleman</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/113489-new-members/topic/2.20beginner.20problems.20with.20an.20induction.20proof/near/491211613\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>And once you've proven the theorem in this new form, you could divide both sides by 2 to get the theorem you really wanted.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Interesting - I've never seen this done before.</p>\n<p>(except MoPs <code>cancel 2 at h</code>)</p>",
        "id": 491211753,
        "sender_full_name": "rzeta0",
        "timestamp": 1735510617
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>For example, you could do this:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kn\">import</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Mathlib</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">Tactic</span>\n\n<span class=\"kn\">def</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">T</span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">ℕ</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">→</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">ℕ</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"bp\">|</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">0</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">=&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">0</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"bp\">|</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">n</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">+</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">1</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">=&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">n</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">+</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">1</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">+</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">T</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">n</span>\n\n<span class=\"kn\">lemma</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">two_T</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">{</span><span class=\"n\">n</span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">ℕ</span><span class=\"o\">}</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">2</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">*</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">T</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">n</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">n</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">*</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">n</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">+</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">1</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"gr\">sorry</span>\n\n<span class=\"kn\">example</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">{</span><span class=\"n\">n</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">ℕ</span><span class=\"o\">}</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">T</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">n</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">n</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">*</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">n</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">+</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">1</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">/</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">2</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"k\">calc</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">T</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">n</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"bp\">_</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">2</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">*</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">T</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">n</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">/</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">2</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">by</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">field_simp</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"bp\">_</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">n</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">*</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">n</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">+</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">1</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">/</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">2</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">by</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">rw</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"n\">two_T</span><span class=\"o\">]</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>Now you can fill in the <code>sorry</code> with an induction proof.</p>",
        "id": 491213156,
        "sender_full_name": "Dan Velleman",
        "timestamp": 1735512110
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>You can first prove <code>2 * T n = n * (n + 1)</code> and then divide both side by <code>2</code>. This is exactly how mathlib handle  Gauss' summation formula.</p>\n<p>See <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=Finset.sum_range_id_mul_two#doc\">docs#Finset.sum_range_id_mul_two</a> and <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=Finset.sum_range_id#doc\">docs#Finset.sum_range_id</a>.</p>",
        "id": 491229552,
        "sender_full_name": "Zhang Qinchuan",
        "timestamp": 1735527760
    }
]